Scope of the Reference Implementation

This release includes:

structural fragments (base, moves, retractions, confirmations)
structural position resolution logic
conflict handling and abstention logic
demo applications (HTML + Python)
outputs and reference outputs
validation traces

SIL defines a deterministic structural motion model where position emerges from structure:

resolve(structure) ->

RESOLVED if structurally consistent final position exists
INCOMPLETE if required structural elements are missing
ABSTAIN if structure is conflicting or unsafe


What This Demonstrates

• position resolution from fragmented structure
• independence from execution order
• independence from timestamps and synchronized clocks
• safe handling of incomplete structural states
• conflict containment without corrupting position
• deterministic convergence across independent nodes
• reproducible structural outcomes
• primitive structural motion without time (structure-derived)


Conformance

An implementation is considered compatible if it preserves:

structure-based position resolution
independence from order as authority
independence from synchronized time
deterministic convergence
reproducibility under equivalent inputs
explicit INCOMPLETE and ABSTAIN handling

Conformance is judged by observable behavior, not internal implementation.


Relationship to Shunyaya Framework

SIL is part of the broader Shunyaya Structural Universal Mathematics (SSUM) framework.

It builds on:

SSUM-Time → time reconstruction without clocks
STOCRS → order-free computation
SSNT → structural traversal without time

SIL extends these principles into structure-derived motion.


